# GoThru 3D API — Non-Technical Overview

**What this is:** A behind-the-scenes service that handles user accounts, project data, and uploaded files for GoThru 3D. The website never communicates with this service directly from the user's browser — everything goes through a secure server-side layer.

---

## User Accounts

### Signing Up

- A user provides their full name, email address, and a password (at least 8 characters)
- The system immediately sends a verification email to the address they provided
- Until they click the verification link, they cannot access the main features of the app

### Signing In

- Users enter their email and password
- If the password is wrong, they see a generic "invalid email or password" message (the system never reveals whether an email address exists in the system)
- If their email hasn't been verified yet, they're told to verify first before they can proceed

### Email Verification

- After signing up, a one-time link is emailed to the user
- Clicking the link confirms their email and unlocks the full app
- Links expire after 24 hours
- Users can request a fresh verification email — limited to 3 requests per hour to prevent abuse

### Password Reset

1. User enters their email on the "Forgot Password" page
2. If the email is in the system, a reset link is sent (valid for 1 hour)
3. The response always says "email sent" — even if the address isn't registered — so no one can probe the system to find out who has an account
4. User clicks the link and sets a new password (at least 8 characters)
5. The link can only be used once

### Staying Signed In

- After signing in, the system issues a secure token to the website
- The website uses this token to identify the user on all future requests
- No passwords are ever stored in plain text — all passwords are encrypted using industry-standard one-way hashing

---

## Projects

Each user can create and manage multiple projects. A project represents a physical space being mapped.

### What a Project Contains

| Field | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| Name | A label for the project (defaults to "Untitled Project") |
| Location | The physical address and map coordinates of the space |
| Floor configuration | Settings describing the number of floors and their dimensions |
| 3D model | The AI-generated digital twin of the space |
| Editor state | The user's work-in-progress from the visual editor |
| Status | Where the project is in its lifecycle (see below) |

### Project Lifecycle

```
draft → scanned → edited → published
                         ↘ unpublished
```

| Status | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| **draft** | Just created; no scan yet |
| **scanned** | Floor plan has been processed by AI |
| **edited** | User has made manual adjustments in the editor |
| **published** | Visible to the public |
| **unpublished** | Was published but taken offline |

### What Users Can Do

- **Create** a new project (with optional name and location)
- **View** a project and all its data
- **Update** the name, floor configuration, 3D model, editor state, or status
- **Delete** a project
- **Publish** a project (only if it's been scanned or edited)
- **Unpublish** a project

---

## Files

Users upload floor plan images or PDFs as part of the scanning process.

- Files are stored securely on the server, organised by user and project
- Each file is linked to a specific project and optionally to a specific floor level
- Users can view their uploaded files or delete them
- Deleting a file removes it from both the server and the database

---

## Email Notifications

Two types of automatic emails are sent:

| Email | When it's sent |
|-------|----------------|
| **Email verification** | After signing up, and when a user requests a resend |
| **Password reset** | When a user requests a password reset |

Email templates and content are managed through an external email platform — the backend simply triggers the right template with the right data (name, link).

---

## Security Highlights

- Passwords are never stored in readable form — only a secure fingerprint of the password is kept
- All account-protected features require a valid signed-in session
- Error messages shown to users never expose internal system details (no database errors, no raw SQL)
- Rate limiting prevents users from spamming the resend-verification or password-reset flows
- The service is called server-to-server only — browsers do not communicate with it directly

---

## Billing & Subscriptions

GoThru uses Stripe to handle paid plans. All billing logic runs server-side — the browser never communicates with Stripe directly.

### How the Checkout Flow Works

```
User clicks "Subscribe" on the billing page
   ↓
GoThru website asks the backend to create a Stripe Checkout Session
   ↓
Backend returns a Stripe-hosted checkout URL
   ↓
User is redirected to Stripe's secure payment page
   ↓
User completes payment on Stripe
   ↓
Stripe redirects user back to GoThru (/billing/success)
   ↓
Stripe sends a webhook event to GoThru backend
   ↓
Backend updates the user's subscription status to "active"
```

### Managing an Existing Subscription

Users with an active subscription can open the Stripe Billing Portal (also hosted by Stripe), where they can:
- Update their payment method
- Download invoices
- Cancel their subscription

The backend generates a portal link when requested and redirects the user there.

### Subscription States

| Status | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| **inactive** | No subscription record, or subscription not yet confirmed |
| **active** | Payment is up to date — full access |
| **past_due** | Payment failed — Stripe will retry |
| **canceled** | Subscription was canceled by the user |

### What Gets Stored

The backend stores a `subscriptions` record per user containing:
- The Stripe Customer ID (used to bill the right person)
- The Stripe Subscription ID (the active or past subscription)
- The current status (`active`, `past_due`, `canceled`, etc.)
- The renewal date (when the current billing period ends)

### Webhooks

Stripe sends automatic notifications when a subscription changes (payment succeeds, fails, or the user cancels). GoThru listens for these at a dedicated endpoint and updates the stored status immediately. These notifications are cryptographically signed by Stripe — GoThru verifies the signature before trusting the data.

---

## Environment Configuration

The service requires the following settings to be configured before deployment:

| Setting | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| Database connection | Where user and project data is stored |
| JWT secret | Used to sign secure session tokens (must be 32+ characters) |
| Email platform API key | Authorises the system to send emails |
| Verification email event name | Which email template to use for account verification |
| Password reset email event name | Which email template to use for password resets |
| App URL | Base URL used to build email links (e.g. the verification link) and Stripe redirect URLs |
| File storage directory | Where uploaded files are saved on the server |
| Port | Which network port the service listens on (default: 8080) |
| CORS allowed origin | Which website domain is allowed to talk to this service (default: http://localhost:3000) |
| Stripe secret key | Authorises the backend to call Stripe's API (never sent to the browser) |
| Stripe webhook secret | Used to verify that webhook notifications genuinely came from Stripe |
| Stripe price ID | Identifies which subscription plan to charge for |
